1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 a6 4. e3 Nc6 5. Bd3 e6 { [%csl Re6][%cal Rc8e6] } (5... h6!? 6. h3! { preparing to play Nf3 without allowing the pin, leading to the normal lines. It's a nice exploit to push h3 whenever black touches the h-pawn. } { [%cal Gg1f3,Rc8g4,Ge1g1] }) (5... Nb4 6. h3!? { same concept, preparing to play Nf3 without allowing ...Bg4 pin. } 6... Nxd3+ 7. cxd3! { we only take back with the queen in the pawn storm. } 7... Bf5 8. Nf3 e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. Bg5!? { This Bd6-Bg5 combo is quite nice specifically after having included cxd3 because we are threatening to take over the center with e4. } { [%cal Ge3e4] } 10... h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6?? 12. e4 dxe4 13. dxe4 Bg6 14. e5! $18 { [%csl Rd6,Rf6][%cal Ge5d6,Ge5f6] }) (5... g6 6. h3! { Making life difficult for the enemy light squared bishop. We just want to play Nf3 without allowing the pin. } { [%csl Rf5,Rg4,Rc8][%cal Gg1f3] } 6... Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. Bh2!? { Sidestepping the ...Nh5-e5 combo. } 9... b5 (9... Nb4 10. a3 Nxd3 11. cxd3! $14 { [%cal Ga1c1,Gb2b4] }) (9... h6 10. Ne2! { [%cal Gc2c4] } 10... Bd7 11. c4 $14 { [%cal Ga1c1,Ga2a3] }) 10. a4! { [%csl Rb5] } 10... b4 11. Na2 a5 12. c3! bxc3 13. Nxc3 $16 { [%csl Gb5,Yc7][%cal Gc3b5,Gh2c7] }) (5... Bg4 6. f3 Bh5 7. g4 Bg6 8. h4 $13 { back in the pawn storm lines. } { [%cal Gh4h5,Gd1d3,Gg1e2,Ge1c1] }) 6. Nf3 Be7 (6... Nh5 7. Bg5! { Generally the best move, not giving away the bishop for free. } { [%csl Rd8][%cal Gg5d8] } (7. O-O!? Nxf4 8. exf4 $14 { this is also possible if Bg5 is not an option. }) 7... f6 8. Bh4 g5?? 9. Nxg5!! { Exploiting the unprotected knight on h5. } { [%csl Rh5][%cal Gd1h5] } 9... fxg5 10. Qxh5+ Kd7 11. Bxg5 $18) 7. O-O Bd7 { [%cal Gc2c4,Gc4f4,Gf4f2,Gf2c2,Be3e4] } 8. e4! { Opening Pandora's box! In the Jobava London our pieces are usually on 'airplane mode' until we manage to get the pawn play rolling. Ideally we are trying to push in the center with e4, but if that's not working (e.g. it's losing a pawn) we can always switch to Ne2-c4. } 8... dxe4 (8... O-O 9. e5! Ne8 10. Ne2 $14 { [%cal Gc2c3,Ge2g3,Gd1d2] }) 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 (9... O-O 10. c3 Nd5 11. Bd2! { The bishop is very useful on this diagonal for kingside duties. Many players instantly go Bg3 where it can become a target. } { [%cal Gd2h6] } (11. Bg3?! f5 12. Ned2? f4 $19 { Ouch! } { [%csl Rg3] }) 11... f5 { [%csl Re4][%cal Gf5e4] } 12. Ng3 Bd6 13. Re1 Nf4 14. Bxf4 Bxf4 15. Bc4 $16 { with long term pressure on the backward e6-pawn. } { [%csl Re6][%cal Gc4e6,Gd1e2] }) 10. Bxe4 O-O 11. c3 Bf6 (11... f5 12. Bc2 $16 { The plan is to attack the backward e6-pawn with all of our pieces. } { [%csl Re6][%cal Gf1e1,Gc2b3] }) 12. Re1 { Simple rule for Pandora's box structure:
-heavy pieces are coming to the middle } { [%cal Gd1e2,Ga1d1] } 12... Re8 (12... Rb8 13. Qe2 { [%cal Ga1d1] } 13... b5 14. Rad1 Na5 15. Ne5 Bxe5 16. dxe5! $16 { Recapturing with the pawn improves our attacking chances because any ...f5-idea to shut down the light squared bishop can be met with en-passant. } { [%cal Gd1d3,Gd3h3] }) 13. Qe2 { [%cal Ga1d1] } 13... e5?? (13... Rb8 14. Rad1 Qc8 15. Ne5 $16 { After we rook lift across the third rank, black's kingside is about to implode. } { [%cal Gd1d3,Gd3h3] }) 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Bxe5 Rxe5 17. Bxh7+ { Thematic little trick, exploiting the unprotected rook. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Ge2e5] } 17... Kxh7 18. Qxe5 $18 *
